    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_677435465" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/677435465" />
    <a title="Brendan Monroe" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/22409011-brendan-monroe"><img alt="Brendan Monroe" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1565543383p2/22409011.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/677435465?book_show_action=true">Jul 25, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Brendan Monroe" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Brendan Monroe" href="/user/show/22409011-brendan-monroe">Brendan Monroe</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22409011-brendan-monroe?shelf=america">america</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer677435465" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4821579162077435349">This is one of those books that I feel I should have rated higher. At least 4 stars. But I simply can&apos;t bring myself to do it. Philip Roth is a terrific writer and this is often cited as perhaps his best book. And the overarching themes in this book are inspired. The setting also, in the reemergent twilight of America&apos;s fixation on sex and purity like a Puritan hangover, couldn&apos;t have been better. Even the title, &apos;The Human Stain&apos; plays so wonderfully on the stain of an all too human sort left b</span>
  <span id="freeText4821579162077435349" style="display:none">This is one of those books that I feel I should have rated higher. At least 4 stars. But I simply can't bring myself to do it. Philip Roth is a terrific writer and this is often cited as perhaps his best book. And the overarching themes in this book are inspired. The setting also, in the reemergent twilight of America's fixation on sex and purity like a Puritan hangover, couldn't have been better. Even the title, 'The Human Stain' plays so wonderfully on the stain of an all too human sort left by a president on an intern's dress, a stain that would lead to his ultimate undoing. <br /><br />Sex is a near constant theme in all of Roth's novels, as well as ruminations on Jewishness and social identity, and this entry is no exception. Roth always manages to insert himself in some form into his novels, sometimes obliquely other times not, but always in some way where we're not entirely sure just how much of what we're reading comes from the author's imaginations and how much comes from his own experiences. <br /><br />I quite like Philip Roth, who has long been one of America's greatest masculine writers, if for no other reason than he has endured his fair share of persecution. Be it for his alleged sexism (though this seems likelier a product of a libelous ex) or for his startling frankness (see Portnoy's Complaint). The fact that he knows his way around a sentence better than any other living American writer certainly helps. And that holds true once again for 'The Human Stain', a beautifully formulated novel.<br /><br />So what then is my issue? What is it that keeps me- much as I want to deny it- from adding that fourth star? Simply, that Roth here "doth digress too much." And it's true too. Roth has us viewing the life of Coleman Silk from the POV of multiple eyewitnesses, and when that isn't happening we're dealing with other issues entirely. The awful trials those back from Vietnam had to endure to try and return to society (though the scene in the Chinese restaurant is one of the novel's best) or entrenched institutional racism, or entrenched institutional classism. All very well put. But for me, I would have much preferred for Roth to have stuck to what I viewed as the most intriguing element of the story, that of persecuters and the persecuted. This is borne out fabulously in the character of Delphine Roux. The epitome of everything one despises about political correctness and the pretentiousness of the academic class. She is so well crafted for instant and lingering despisal and hate that you just know Roth must have known a similar Roux (and haven't we all?).<br /><br />As a result of all these digressions, this book was something of a slog- until the magnificent fifth and final act of the story began, the climax of which is so perfect and well-done that it just about makes up for the slogging that came before.<br /><br />In review then, a worthy and laudable book. One of those which, after reading and just can't summoning up the enthusiasm to wholeheartedly endorse, leaves you apologizing to Roth with an "it's not you, it's me"</span>
  <a data-text-id="4821579162077435349" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


