<span id="freeTextContainer13969836345566998373">The only Roth I&apos;d ever read was Portnoy, back when it came out (practically), and the Plot Against America - which didn&apos;t impress me at all. So I came to this book, which I listened to on audible, with a prejudice against Roth. I didn&apos;t like him, thought he was a fake, he didn&apos;t &quot;look&quot; like much of a writer to me, etc. etc. I probably wouldn&apos;t have gotten very far if I had been reading -- listening being a very different experience. (I do so much driving, that I listen to these things in drive-t</span>
  <span id="freeText13969836345566998373" style="display:none">The only Roth I'd ever read was Portnoy, back when it came out (practically), and the Plot Against America - which didn't impress me at all. So I came to this book, which I listened to on audible, with a prejudice against Roth. I didn't like him, thought he was a fake, he didn't "look" like much of a writer to me, etc. etc. I probably wouldn't have gotten very far if I had been reading -- listening being a very different experience. (I do so much driving, that I listen to these things in drive-time, basically). So I was surprised at how much I liked this book, and also at how good it was. Once again, yet another of my long-term biases have fallen apart....</span>
