<div id="review_433470080" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/433470080" />
    <a title="Alex" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8882313-alex"><img alt="Alex" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1553312028p2/8882313.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/433470080?book_show_action=true">May 13, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Alex" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Alex" href="/user/show/8882313-alex">Alex</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer433470080" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1739150332129675403">SPOILERS<br/><br/>The impending release of Blake Bailey’s gargantuan biography of Philip Roth was my impetus to read a few more Roth novels this year. Although I would appear to be in the stereotypical Roth-reader demographic (atheist, Jewish, male) I only came to Roth in the last ten years (after seeing a copy of American Pastoral on my grandmother’s bookshelves). Even though I had read Portnoy’s Complaint earlier in the year and had picked up The Human Stain, I was still reticent to get Bailey’s book. I</span>
  <span id="freeText1739150332129675403" style="display:none">SPOILERS<br /><br />The impending release of Blake Bailey’s gargantuan biography of Philip Roth was my impetus to read a few more Roth novels this year. Although I would appear to be in the stereotypical Roth-reader demographic (atheist, Jewish, male) I only came to Roth in the last ten years (after seeing a copy of American Pastoral on my grandmother’s bookshelves). Even though I had read Portnoy’s Complaint earlier in the year and had picked up The Human Stain, I was still reticent to get Bailey’s book. It felt bloated, had received some mixed reviews, and whether Roth had asked him to or not Bailey seemed to have at least partly used the biography to settle some scores, especially with his ex wives. I did end up getting an audiobook version but when the horrible accusations of sexual impropriety and assault against Bailey surfaced I just couldn’t bring myself to even consider reading the biography and returned it. <br /> <br />Nonetheless, there was a degree of irony of being in the middle of The Human Stain when the Bailey scandal erupted, considering the themes Roth explored in it. The Human Stain is the final book in the American Trilogy (after American Pastoral and I Married A Communist) and was one of the many acclaimed and awarded novels he wrote in the 1990s and early 2000s, a prolific period that included Operation Shylock, Sabbath’s Theatre, and The Plot Against America in addition to the Trilogy. The Human Stain is also one of Roth’s more controversial books and frankly one of his most dated and less compelling works. Reading The Plot Against America in 2016 as Trump rose to prominence felt like Roth saw the future and was warning us. Reading The Human Stain felt like Roth was harkening back to simpler times when prejudiced attitudes weren’t called out and were allowed to go unchallenged. <br /><br />The Human Stain situates itself in the late 1990s, with the Clinton impeachment hearings as the backdrop and what Roth portrays as a period of puritanical overbearingness, where small indiscretions result in disproportionate consequences and ruined lives. Like the other three American Trilogy books, we hear the story through the words of Nathan Zuckerman, this time telling us about a beleaguered former professor and dean, Coleman Silk. Silk’s demise began when he referred to two perennially absent students as “spooks”, a racially charged term that results in the University admonishing Silk for using since both the students were African American. He’s quickly abandoned by colleagues he had brought on as professors to the school and left out to dry by his replacement as dean, Delphine Roux, a more modern academic who embraces critical race and gender approaches to studying subjects that irked an old guard. Silk’s wife dies suddenly in the midst of his battle with the university and in a fit of desperation he resigns his position and begins to write a book excoriating the university for what they did. He eventually decides to not publish the book (this very much parallels Roth’s own obsessive madness when his ex-wife wrote a tell all memoire that put him in very poor light) and begins dating a much younger custodial worker (the age and power discrepancy on full display), an act that also manages to irk his nemesis Roux.<br /><br />The big twist in The Human Stain, however, is that Silk in fact is an African American man, who chose decades earlier to pass as a white man, become Jewish, and cut off his family from his life. He never told his wife, his children, or any of his friends about his background, and despite accusations of racism lobbed toward him lived with this secret. There is a moment where Roth could have used this remarkable revelation to explore not just questions of identity but also the interiority of Silk’s thinking, how his choice to runaway from himself resulted in eventual disaster and how his internal struggle left him vulnerable, unable to properly respond to the adversity, left him eager to lash out and blame others. It would have made for a better book, a more self-aware exploration that revealed more about Roth’s internal struggle rather than his penchant to blame others. Alas it was not to be.<br /><br />In a recent review of the Bailey situation, Jeet Heer noted:<br /><br />“A typical Philip Roth novel is about a controlling, willful man who tries to bring an unsustainable order to his life only to be blindsided by the perversity of human nature. In the best of Roth’s novels, that perversity resides in the protagonist. In the weaker and more defensive books, perversity is assigned to others—often ex-wives or children.”<br /><br />In The Human Stain, Roth goes down that much less interesting path. Delphine Roux becomes the villain, the architect of Silk’s demise, who continues to obsess about Silk well after he has left his position at the university. And in one of the most painfully bad and predictable plot points, Roux’s obsession is rooted not hate but in a buried desire and love for Silk. Her inability to have Silk results in her seeking to destroy him. Delphine Roux is the character that comes to mind when reading Laura Marsh’s excellent review of the Bailey biography in the New Republic that noted “Women in this book are forever screeching, berating, flying into a rage, and storming off, as if their emotions exist solely for the purpose of sapping a man’s creative energies.” <br /><br />But Roth doesn’t just confirm his harshest critics worst charges, his poor treatment of women characters, he goes further exploring other intellectual curiosities and expressing opinions that could just as easily have come from the mouth of Jordan Peterson. His characters harp on the emergence of new perspectives in academia, questioning the value of seeing classic texts through the lens of race or gender. Painfully, Roth chooses to have a Black woman, Coleman’s sister, articulate this most clearly, herself not impressed with insertions of race into larger academic conversations. That choice is not accidental and speaks to how weak the position with the white male (whose perspectives have dominated for so long) having to express his frustration through a fictional character of colour. <br /><br />Roth cheats us as readers by going down this predictable and frankly tired path. The Human Stain is brilliantly written at points. The exploration of torn and blurry racial identities is where this novel is at its best. But just as in life, Roth couldn’t take us there, he had to use these pages for his axe grinding and the work is frankly weakened as a result. <br /><br />I stand by liking of Roth as a writer, warts and all. He was a bitter and angry man who held grudges to a fault and this not only weakened his writing but also likely allowed him to choose a biographer like Bailey, whose ruin will certainly tarnish Roth’s legacy. Roth is a complicated author. At this best, he expresses a chaotic anxiety in the most entertaining fashion. He explores issues of Jewish identity and complex historical moments with both solemnity and humour. But when he misses, when he resorts to his worse impulses, the problematics in his writing (his misogynous depiction of women most obviously), it really feels disappointing. Because it is Roth, you can see the great novel in The Human Stain. But because it is Roth, you know exactly how he self-sabotaged it.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1739150332129675403" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

